<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-279-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 279 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 19 1990 v7 n12 p35(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Centrex redux. (Centrex vs. private branch exchange services)(buyers guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Briere, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is and probably will be no clear winner in the battlebetween Centrex services and private branch exchanges (PBX).andP;  Acomparison of features shows that Centrex and PBX functionality isfairly equal; Centrex is PBX-like switching capability provided bylocal carriers and a network-based alternative to PBX systems.andO;Centrex's ties to the public network give it the potential to be aplatform for future intelligent network offerings.andP;  Some of thearguments in favor of Centrex are small technological risk,continual upgrading, 24-hour maintenance, minimal impact on workenvironment, rate-stabilization, uniform call distribution (UCD)features and automatic route selection (ARS) features.andP;  Pricing isthe only real problem Centrex poses.andP;  Since Centrex is offered bylocal telephone companies, rates are subject to regulation andprice-competitiveness is limited.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Centrex Telephone ServicePBXDirectoriesTelecommunicationsCost Benefit AnalysisFuture of ComputingCommunications Service SuppliersCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>